        problem: "A 10.00 cm³ blood sample is treated with 25.00 cm³ of 0.0200 mol dm⁻³ K₂Cr₂O₇. The unreacted Cr is back-titrated with 0.0500 mol dm⁻³ Fe²⁺ solution, requiring 18.60 cm³. The simplified oxidation is: 2Cr²⁺ → 2Cr³⁺ (each Cr oxidises one unit of ethanol). Calculate the moles of Cr²⁺ that reacted with ethanol.",
        application: "Moles of Cr added = 0.0200 × (25.00/1000) = 5.00 × 10⁻⁴ mol. Moles of unreacted Cr titrated by Fe²⁺ = 0.0500 × (18.60/1000) = 9.30 × 10⁻⁴ mol. Moles of Cr that reacted with ethanol = 5.00 × 10⁻⁴ − 9.30 × 10⁻⁴ = negative — this signals a stoichiometry adjustment is needed in the real problem. In the real Cr₂O₇²⁻ method, 2 Cr(VI) oxidise 1 ethanol in a 3:2 ratio. This contextual scenario illustrates back titration logic: excess − remaining = reacted.",
