        answer: "Ethanol does not produce a sharp colour change at the equivalence point with K₂Cr₂O₇ — there is no convenient indicator for this redox reaction under forensic conditions, and the reaction is slow. A back titration avoids this: a measured excess of oxidant is added (ensuring complete reaction), and the easier-to-titrate Fe²⁺/Cr³⁺ system is used for the back step, which has a clear colour change at its equivalence point.",
