        answer: "Complete combustion fully oxidises carbon to CO₂ — the maximum oxidation state of carbon. This releases the maximum enthalpy because the C=O bonds in CO₂ are extremely strong (802 kJ/mol each). Incomplete combustion produces CO, where carbon is only partially oxidised — weaker C≡O triple bond product, but more importantly the carbon is not fully oxidised so further energy release is possible if CO is subsequently burned to CO₂. CO is therefore both a toxicological hazard and an energy source.",
